"Simmonds P.G., Greally B.R., Olivier S., Nickless G., Cooke K.M., Dietz R.N.","The background atmospheric concentrations of cyclic perfluorocarbon tracers determined by negative ion-chemical ionization mass spectrometry",2002,"Atmospheric Environment","36","13",,"2147","2156",,,10.1016/S1352-2310(02)00194-2,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036279912&partnerID=40&md5=daf561fc9cdef212965e30633307d21e","School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Sira Ltd., South Hill, Chislehurst, Kent BR7 5EH, United Kingdom; Environmental Sciences Department, Brookhaven National Laboratory, Upton, NY 11973, United States","Simmonds, P.G., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Greally, B.R., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Olivier, S., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Nickless, G., School of Chemistry, University of Bristol, Bristol BS8 1TS, United Kingdom; Cooke, K.M., Sira Ltd., South Hill, Chislehurst, Kent BR7 5EH, United Kingdom; Dietz, R.N., Environmental Sciences Department, Brookhaven National Laboratory, Upton, NY 11973, United States","The background atmospheric mixing ratios for a range of cyclic perfluorocarbons (cyclic-PFCs), widely used in atmospheric dispersion studies, have been measured by gas chromatography-mass spectrometry in negative ion-chemical ionization mode. Background concentrations range from &lt;1fll-1 to &gt;10fll-1, where femtolitre is expressed as parts in 1015 (ppqv). Because of their very long atmospheric lifetimes (&gt;3000yr) the present day concentrations represent the accumulated emissions from all sources, although significant commercial production did not commence until the 1960s. Cyclic-PFCs are potent greenhouse gases; however, their atmospheric concentrations are currently so low as to make an insignificant contribution to global warming. © 2002 Elsevier Science 